$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{\partial L}{\partial x} &= \lambda \cdot (2x) \\
\frac{\partial L}{\partial y} &= \lambda \cdot (2y) \\
\intertext{Given the constraint $x^2 + y^2 = 1$, we can substitute to find $\lambda$:}
2x &= \lambda \cdot (2x) \\
2y &= \lambda \cdot (2y)
\end{aligned}
$$

$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{\partial L}{\partial x} &= \lambda \cdot (2x) \\
\frac{\partial L}{\partial y} &= \lambda \cdot (2y) \\
\intertext{Given the constraint $x^2 + y^2 = 1$, we can substitute to find $\lambda$:}
2x &= 2\lambda x \\
2y &= 2\lambda y
\end{aligned}
$$


